metadata.name: Sea of Shapes #112
metadata.description:
This program was inspired by the 2022 Genuary prompt "Make a sea of shapes." It is an abstract and geometric representation of water and waves. I tried to capture the many different possible states of a sea (windy, breezy, calm etc.) by changing parameters within the program for different outputs.

Press 'p' while on Live View to save a high quality (4000x4000) png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js

Licensed under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #465
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: Emergence #45
metadata.description: This project was supposed to be released in a global one containing also my previous one Rupture. However, even if they were close in the intent by achieving some interesting pattern through a very sensitive balance between numerous parameters, they have resulted in output that can clearly appeal to different sensitivities. Then, I have prefered to separate them (and it was a bit easier to deal with the code ^^).

metadata.name: (°)3/V4///3 XX #13
Whisper #46
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: Refractions #7
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, April 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Solace #114
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.

metadata.name: Extreme Ways #217
metadata.description:
« Extreme ways are back again
Extreme places I didn't know
I broke everything new again
Everything that I'd owned
I threw it out the windows, came along
Extreme ways I know move apart The colors of my sea
Perfect color me… »
Song/Lyrics by Moby

All pieces are broken again and again…

Controls
Extreme ways contains some interactivity if you wish to explore.
Since this artwork is complex it takes time to draw, be patient. 

Press h in live mode to list the possibilities and see tips for interactivity usage.
Key ’s’  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key ‘c’ : Change colors
Key ‘m’ : Change main style
Key ‘d’ : Change drawing style
…
 

Pricing
Proposed as a Dutch Auction 11-9-7-5 tez with a step every 10 minutes.


Features
Main features are listed : Main style, drawing style, etc…
I do not think rarity will be a good indicator of the quality of the output.
Trust your taste and buy on the secondary what you like…
Lots of parameters are used internally to ensure a large variety in the outputs.

metadata.name: Machine Spirit #184
metadata.description:
Machine Spirit picks up where Equilibrium and Equanimity left off. Notwithstanding my love for generative mountains, trees, and (especially) cities, my personal artistic quest remains to produce an algorithm that generates convincing abstract art in the style of Richter and Rothko. The project you are looking at is my best attempt yet.

Trigger warning: some iterations produce rapidly flashing colors which may pose a risk of seizure to people with photosensitive epilepsy or similar conditions.

While the final result is a static image, the live view visualizes how the image is generated. It goes something like this: you start with a grid of cells in random colors, and you feed that into a carefully customized cellular automaton, where the color of each cell is determined by the color of that cell and its neighbours in the previous generation. If you end up with a single color over-powering all the others, or too many different fragmented colors, you start over. But when you reach a stable state with two or three colors, you have achieved your goal: a mathematical balance in color and composition that tends to be aesthetically pleasing as well. You then select a suitable canvas color and run a more computationally intensive rendering process, which makes the end result look more like physical paint on canvas, while retaining the subtle traces of its digital origins.

Press [b]leed, [c]anvas or [d]ensity in the live view to cycle through variations, or [p]rint to save a high resolution capture.

All iterations eventually converge to a stable state, but in theory this could last arbitrarily long, and on rare occasions it may take longer than 5 minutes, in which case the captured preview will be different from the final result. This artwork is fully generative and was hand-coded in 7,500 characters of plain JavaScript code. I didn't use any libraries, but I did take inspiration from an essay by Tyler Hobbs on polygon deformation techniques.

Forever limited to 250 editions on the Tezos blockchain. I truly hope you will enjoy yours. London, March 2022.
